    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Dissect the alveolar gas equation step by step: starting from PAO₂ = FiO₂ × (PB − PH₂O) − PaCO₂/RQ, identify what each term represents, why water vapour must be subtracted, what RQ means and why it is typically 0.8, and how to calculate PiO₂ at altitude (where PB is reduced). Apply the equation to: (a) room air at sea level; (b) 40% O₂ at sea level; (c) room air at 3000 m altitude (PB ~526 mmHg). Verify that the A-a gradient is normal in (a) and state what a raised gradient indicates.",
        "Dissect the oxygen content equation (CaO₂ = Hb × 1.34 × SaO₂ + 0.003 × PaO₂): derive where the constant 1.34 comes from (each gram of haemoglobin can carry 1.34 mL O₂ when fully saturated — derived from the molecular weight of haemoglobin and four O₂ molecules per tetramer). Calculate the dissolved O₂ contribution as a percentage of total CaO₂ in a normal patient and at 100% O₂ — confirm that even at PaO₂ of 600 mmHg, dissolved O₂ (1.8 mL/dL) is only ~15% of total. Explain why hyperbaric oxygen can occasionally be life-saving despite the small dissolved fraction.",
        "Dissect the CO₂ transport pathway in reverse (from pulmonary artery to pulmonary vein): (1) deoxygenated blood arrives at lung capillary; (2) O₂ diffuses in, binds haemoglobin; (3) oxygenation reduces CO₂ affinity (Haldane effect) → carbaminohaemoglobin releases CO₂; (4) HCO₃⁻ re-enters RBC in exchange for Cl⁻ (reverse chloride shift); (5) HCO₃⁻ + H⁺ → H₂CO₃ → CO₂ + H₂O (carbonic anhydrase); (6) CO₂ diffuses into alveolus. Draw each step as a flow diagram and annotate the direction of each ion and molecule at each step.",
        "Dissect a published COPD management guideline (GOLD guidelines, available online): identify where spirometry criteria are used to stage severity (GOLD 1–4), what FEV₁% predicted threshold defines each stage, what the physiological rationale is for each therapeutic step, and where the target SaO₂ recommendation for oxygen therapy is stated. Annotate every clinical recommendation with the underlying respiratory physiology concept from this lesson.",
        "Perform a simulated ABG interpretation exercise using published online ABG simulators: complete at least 20 cases spanning all four primary acid-base disorders plus mixed disorders. For each case, write your four-step interpretation, calculate the A-a gradient where PaO₂ is provided, and state the most likely clinical diagnosis. Track your accuracy rate over the 20 cases and identify which disorder type you most frequently misinterpret — then review the specific physiology for that disorder."
    ]
