    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Dissect the Starling equation at four clinical extremes: (1) normal — calculate net filtration at arterial and venous ends; (2) left heart failure — raise Pc to 40 mmHg and recalculate; (3) hypoalbuminaemia — reduce πc to 12 mmHg and recalculate; (4) lymphatic obstruction — maintain normal Starling values but set lymphatic drainage capacity to zero. For each scenario, predict: direction of net filtration, whether reabsorption at the venous end compensates, and whether clinically visible oedema results. Connect each calculation to a real clinical condition.",
        "Dissect the T cell activation two-signal model: signal 1 = TCR-MHC-peptide interaction; signal 2 = CD28 (on T cell) — B7 (on APC). Then extend to three-signal model: signal 3 = cytokine environment (IL-12 → Th1; IL-4 → Th2; TGF-β + IL-6 → Th17; TGF-β alone → Treg). For each signal, write: what provides it, what happens to the T cell if it is missing (anergy for missing signal 2), and which drug or pathogen exploits that vulnerability.",
        "Dissect the germinal centre reaction step by step: (1) B cell activated by antigen + T helper cell in primary follicle; (2) B cell proliferates rapidly forming germinal centre; (3) somatic hypermutation introduces random mutations into variable region genes; (4) antigen selection — B cells with higher affinity receptors bind follicular dendritic cell-displayed antigen and receive survival signals; low-affinity cells undergo apoptosis; (5) class switching under Tfh cytokine direction (IL-4 → IgE; IFN-γ → IgG; TGF-β → IgA); (6) high-affinity IgG-producing plasma cells and memory B cells exported. For each step, annotate what would happen if it were blocked (e.g. no affinity maturation if AID enzyme is absent — Hyper-IgM syndrome variant).",
        "Dissect the HIV infection cycle and its lymphatic consequences: (1) HIV gp120 binds CD4 + CCR5/CXCR4 co-receptor on CD4+ T cell; (2) fusion and entry; (3) reverse transcription of viral RNA → DNA; (4) integration into host chromosome (provirus); (5) viral replication in lymph node germinal centres (greatest viral burden during latency); (6) progressive CD4+ T cell depletion — months to years; (7) eventual loss of lymph node architecture (burnt-out follicles visible on biopsy); (8) CD4+ count < 200/μL → AIDS-defining opportunistic infections. At each step, annotate which antiretroviral drug class (NRTI, NNRTI, protease inhibitor, integrase inhibitor, entry inhibitor) acts to block that step.",
        "Perform a virtual lymph node cell sorting experiment using an online flow cytometry simulator: set up forward scatter (cell size) vs side scatter (granularity) to identify lymphocytes as a distinct population. Then apply CD3-FITC (T cell marker), CD19-PE (B cell marker), and CD56-APC (NK cell marker). Calculate the percentage of each population in a normal lymph node sample. Then simulate a CLL (chronic lymphocytic leukaemia) sample (markedly elevated CD19+ B cells) and a T cell lymphoma sample (markedly elevated CD3+ T cells). For each abnormal result, state the clinical presentation you would expect and connect the flow cytometry finding to the underlying pathology."
    ]
