    practiceRoutines: [
        "Hormone profile drawing drill: on a blank axis (day 1–28), draw all four hormones (FSH, LH, oestrogen, progesterone) from memory. Check against a reference graph. Mark every point where you drew the wrong peak height, wrong timing, or wrong shape. Redo the graph immediately. Repeat daily for one week. Track your error type — most students repeatedly err on the relative heights of the FSH and LH peaks and on the timing of the progesterone peak.",
        "Gametogenesis ploidy drill: given a random stage name (e.g. 'secondary spermatocyte', 'first polar body', 'primary oocyte at ovulation'), immediately state the ploidy (2n or n), the number of chromatids per cell, and what division produced this cell. Do this for 10 cells in under 3 minutes. Errors on ploidy between primary and secondary spermatocyte/oocyte are the most common — focus extra repetition there.",
        "HPG axis pharmacology drill: given a drug (combined OCP, clomiphene, GnRH agonist long protocol, exogenous FSH), draw the HPG axis and mark: (1) where the drug acts; (2) what it does to GnRH, FSH, and LH levels; (3) what it does to follicle development; (4) whether ovulation is inhibited or stimulated. Do this for five drugs in sequence without notes.",
        "Clinical scenario rapid-fire practice: read a two-sentence scenario (e.g. 'FSH elevated, LH normal, oestrogen low, AMH very low — what is the diagnosis and what level of the HPG axis is affected?'). Write your answer in 90 seconds. Check. Repeat with 10 different scenarios covering: hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism, premature ovarian insufficiency, PCOS, hyperprolactinaemia, and normal mid-luteal phase. Track which scenario type you consistently misdiagnose.",
        "Fertilisation event timing practice: given a timeline (ovulation = hour 0), place each event at its correct timeframe: capacitation (already ongoing in female tract), acrosome reaction (upon zona contact), fast polyspermy block (seconds), cortical reaction (within minutes), Meiosis II completion (within 1 hour of sperm entry), pronuclei formation (4–6 hours), syngamy (within 12 hours), first cleavage (24–30 hours). Any errors indicate gaps in sequence knowledge — return to the seven-panel diagram."
    ],

    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Examine the microscopic anatomy of the testis by dissecting the spermatogenesis sequence from a tubule cross-section: start at the basement membrane (spermatogonia) and trace cell types centripetally toward the lumen (spermatocytes → spermatids → spermatozoa). For each cell type, record nucleus size and shape, cytoplasm amount, and position in the tubule. Connect each observation to the meiotic or spermiogenic event that produced those morphological features.",
        "Dissect the hormonal mechanism of the COCP step by step: (1) identify the two hormonal components (synthetic oestrogen + progestogen); (2) trace their action at the hypothalamus (reduced GnRH pulse frequency); (3) trace their action at the pituitary (reduced FSH and LH secretion); (4) identify the ovarian consequence (no follicle development, no oestrogen rise, no LH surge); (5) identify two additional mechanisms (cervical mucus thickening, endometrial atrophy); (6) predict what a day 12 hormone profile would look like in a pill-taker vs a non-pill-taker. At each step, state which component (oestrogen or progestogen) is primarily responsible.",
        "Dissect the process of IVF in stages and connect each stage to underlying physiology: (1) pituitary suppression (GnRH agonist/antagonist) — why needed; (2) ovarian stimulation (FSH injections) — what normally limits follicle number and how stimulation overcomes this; (3) ovulation trigger (hCG or GnRH agonist) — what this mimics and why timing matters; (4) oocyte retrieval — what stage oocytes are at and why; (5) fertilisation (conventional IVF or ICSI) — what each method requires from sperm; (6) embryo culture — what developmental milestones are observed; (7) embryo transfer — what the endometrium must provide for implantation; (8) luteal support — why progesterone supplementation is needed specifically after IVF.",
        "Dissect a published human hormone profile graph from a paper on the menstrual cycle: (a) identify the day of ovulation (LH peak); (b) calculate the follicular phase length and luteal phase length; (c) identify the oestrogen peak just before the LH surge; (d) measure the progesterone peak day and value; (e) determine whether the corpus luteum was functional (progesterone > 30 nmol/L mid-luteal); (f) assess whether the graph shows the secondary oestrogen rise in the mid-luteal phase. Write a one-paragraph interpretation of the cycle as if reporting a clinical result.",
        "Perform a virtual or laboratory pregnancy test at defined days post-ovulation using serial hCG dilutions: test strips at hCG concentrations 0, 5, 10, 25, 50, 100, 500 mIU/mL. Record the lowest concentration giving a positive result (detection threshold). Convert this to days post-implantation using hCG doubling time (~48 hours). Calculate on what day post-ovulation the test would first become positive, assuming implantation on day 8 and initial hCG secretion at 50 mIU/mL on day 8. Compare your calculation to manufacturer claims and commercial test sensitivity specifications."
    ]
